@node Introduction "xPlay 1.1 - Introduction"

@{fg shine}Why @{i}another@{ui} program to play sound samples?@{fg text}
------------------------------------------

If sound samples are big, its handy to be able to play them directly
off disk.  There are already many programs that can do this.  But
what if you have compressed them (to save disk space) using xpk?

Use xPlay.

@{fg shine}Features@{fg text}
--------

    - Plays samples while loading from disk, so does not need much ram
    - Plays samples compressed with xpk
    - Plays IFF or RAW (mono only)
    - System friendly (uses audio.device)
    - Useable from workbench, as a default tool or by shift clicking
    - Useable from cli
    - Supports pattern matching (from cli)
    - Progress indicator (in cli)
    - Can abort playing with CTRL-C and CTRL-D
    - Pure executable (can be made resident)

@endnode

@node Requirements "xPlay 1.1 - Requirements"

@{FG shine}Requirements@{FG text}
------------

I have kickstart 3.1, but I think it will work on kickstart 2 or above.
xPlay also needs xpk library version 2 or above.

@endnode

@node Usage "xPlay 1.1 - Usage"

@{FG shine}Installation@{FG text}
------------

Drag the xPlay program to your utilities drawer.
Put the documentation anywhere you like.

@{FG shine}Use from CLI@{FG text}
------------

Template : xPlay SAMPLES/M/A, ALL/S, V=VOLUME/N, F=FREQUENCY/N, ...
...P=PERIOD/N, PRI=PRIORITY/N, D=DOUBLE/S, M=MONO/S, Q=QUIET/S, ...
...FL=FILTER/S, NFL=NOFILTER/S, PC/S

    SAMPLES/M/A:
        A list of file names or AmigaDOS patterns to play.

    ALL/S:
        A switch to recursively scan through subdirectories.

    VOLUME/N:
        A value between 0 and 64 to specify the output volume.  The
        loudest volume is 64.  Defaults to value stored in sample.

    FREQUENCY/N:
        The output frequency.  Defaults to value stored in sample.
        Either specify frequency or period or none.

    PERIOD/N:
        The output period.  Defaults to value stored in sample.
        Either specify frequency or period or none.

    PRIORITY/N:
        The channel allocation precedence.  Defaults to 0.

    DOUBLE/S:
        Use all 4 audio channels for replay (maximum volume).

    MONO/S:
        Use only one channel for replay.

    QUIET/S:
        No progress indicator.

    FILTER/S:
        Turn ON the audio filter.  Default is to leave filter as it is.

    NOFILTER/S:
        Turn OFF the audio filter.  Default is to leave filter as it is.

    PC/S:
        Replay the data in UNSIGNED format (this way you can listen to
        8 bit WAV and VOC files as RAW data).

@{FG shine}Use from WorkBench@{FG text}
------------------

Use xPlay as the default tool for sound project icons.

Alternatively, to select files for xPlay to play, click once on
the xPlay icon, then shift-click the sound samples that you want
to play.  Shift-double-click on the last sample.

xPlay will examine each sample's icon for the following tooltypes :-

    VOLUME = 1 to 64
        Set the playback volume.  64 is the loudest.  If you do not
        specify this value, xPlay will use the value stored in the
        sample.

    FILTER = ON | OFF
        Turn the hardware sound filter on or off during the playback.
        The filter will be restored when the samples has finished
        playing.  Default is to leave the filter as it is.

    FREQUENCY = number
        Set the playback frequency.  Higher values playback faster
        and higher pitched.  Defaults to value stored in sample.
        Frequency overrides period.

    PERIOD = number
        Set the playback period.  Overiden by frequency.

    MONO
        Play back sample in left channel only.  Defaults to playing
        sample in both left and right channel.

    DOUBLE
        Use two left and two right channels.  If used with MONO,
        will use two left channels.

@{FG shine}Stopping the sound@{FG text}
------------------

You can halt replay by sending the program a CTRL-C.  You can also
halt the current sample, and move on to the next by sending the
program a CTRL-D.

@endnode

